U.S. anti-China technology war
From New York — the worst diplomatic decision made by the previous generation (or even earlier generations) of Americans was the 2003 "War of Choice" launched against Iraq, which claimed to aim at eliminating — — non-existent — — weapons of mass destruction.
The necessity of understanding the flawed logic behind this catastrophic decision has become unprecedentedly significant, as the same logic is now being used to justify similar U.S. misleading policies.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then-Vice President Richard Cheney, who argued that even if the risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into terrorist hands was small (for example, 1 percent), we should still act as if it were certain to happen.
But this line of reasoning almost always leads to incorrect decisions.
However, the United States and some of its allies are now using Cheneyism to attack China's technology.
According to the U.S. government, since we cannot be certain that Chinese technology is safe, we should respond to and ban it by understanding it as inherently harmful.
Correct decisions apply probability estimates to various alternative options.
A generation ago, U.S. policymakers should not only have considered the 1% risk (alleged) of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists, but also the 99% risk of going to war based on multiple flawed premises.
By solely emphasizing that 1% risk, Cheney (and many others) diverted public attention, leading people to overlook the fact that the Iraq War lacked justification and would seriously undermine the stability of the Middle East and global politics.
The problem with Cheneyism is not only that it takes action based on minor risks without considering the potentially high costs, but that politicians always stir up fear for some ulterior motives.
This is yet another thing that the U.S. leaders are doing: inciting panic over Chinese tech companies by pointing out and exaggerating certain minor risks.
The most relevant (but not the only) case is the US government's attack on the communications technology company Huawei.
The United States is gradually closing its domestic market for the company and is striving to eliminate its global operations.
Like Iraq, the United States may ultimately cause an unjustified geopolitical disaster.
I have worked in developing countries and have been closely following Huawei's technological advancements, as I believe 5G and other digital technologies can provide significant momentum toward achieving the United Nations' Sustainable Development Goals, including the eradication of poverty.
I have also engaged in similar interactions with other telecommunications companies and encouraged the industry to enhance its actions towards achieving the Sustainable Development Goals.
I once wrote a short introduction for a report Huawei prepared on this subject (without any compensation), and as a result, I was criticized by some hostile Chinese observers. In response, I asked senior industry figures and government officials if there was any evidence that Huawei had engaged in improper conduct, and the repeated answer I received was that Huawei's conduct was no different from that of other reputable industry leaders.
Nevertheless, the U.S. government still believes that Huawei's 5G equipment could pose a threat to global security.
U.S. officials claimed that the "backdoors" retained in Huawei's software or hardware might enable the Chinese government to carry out surveillance worldwide.
They pointed out that China's laws require Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But the facts are right here now.
Huawei's 5G equipment is inexpensive and of high quality, currently leading many competitors and beginning to be promoted.
Its high performance stems from substantial investments in R&D over many years, scale economy effects, and extensive experience navigating the Chinese digital market.
Considering the importance of this technology to its sustainable development, it would be clearly unwise for low-income economies around the world to reject the early rollout of 5G.
However, despite lacking any evidence of backdoors, the United States continues to lobby the world to stay away from Huawei.
The U.S. claim is universal.
As one American Federal Communications Commissioner put it: "The country that owns 5G will lead in related innovation and set the standards for the rest of the world, and this country is unlikely to be the United States at the moment."
Other countries — especially the United Kingdom — have not found any backdoors in Huawei's software and hardware.
Even if a backdoor is discovered in the future, it is almost certainly possible to close it at that time.
The debate over Huawei has been intense in Germany as well, because the U.S. government has threatened to reduce intelligence cooperation unless authorities keep Huawei's 5G technology out.
Perhaps under pressure from the United States, the director of Germany's Federal Intelligence Service recently made a statement similar to Cheneyism: "Infrastructure is not a field suitable for a group that cannot be fully trusted."
But he was unable to present any evidence of specific crimes.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel fought behind the scenes to open up the market to Huawei.
Ironically, the U.S. complaints partly reflect its own surveillance activities both domestically and internationally — though this is no longer news.
Chinese equipment may make it more difficult for the U.S. government to carry out secret surveillance.
However, any unjustified surveillance by a government should cease.
The independent supervision conducted by the United Nations to reduce such activities should become part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should choose diplomacy and institutional guarantees rather than engage in a technological warfare.
The United States' threat of banning Huawei's potentially harmful influence is not limited to the early rollout of 5G networks, but also poses significant risks to the rule-based trading system.
Nowadays, the United States is no longer an unquestioned global technological leader, and President Trump and his advisors do not want to compete within a rules-based system.
Their goal is to curb China's technological ascent.
They also tried to erase the organization by paralyzing the World Trade Organization's dispute settlement mechanism, which similarly reflects their model of global rules.
If the Trump administration could "successfully" divide the world into different technological camps, the risk of future conflicts would double.
After World War II, the United States promoted open trade, which not only improved global efficiency and expanded the American technology market, but also reversed the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
Part of the reason for the collapse was the protectionist tariffs imposed by the United States under the 1930 Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act, which exacerbated the Great Depression, contributed to Hitler's rise, and ultimately helped trigger the outbreak of World War II.
Just as in other fields, in international affairs, inciting fear and acting upon it rather than following evidence is a path leading to self-destruction.
Let us stick to reason, evidence, and rules; this is the safest approach.
Let us establish an independent monitoring body to reduce the threat of any country using the global network to monitor other countries or launch cyber warfare.
In this way, the world can quickly leverage breakthrough digital technologies to achieve global well-being.
